\section*{Chapter Two Part One: Displaying and Describing One Categorical Variable}


Recall from Chapter One that categorical variables are variables that take on \underline{\hspace{3cm}} as \underline{\hspace{3cm}}. 

There are three main ways we extract information about categorical variables:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Counts(frequencies)}: \vskip 1in
  \item \textbf{Proportions}: \vskip 1in
  \item \textbf{Percentages}: \vskip 1in
\end{itemize}

When we encounter a categorical variable in \textit{the wild}, it is often useful to 
\begin{enumerate}
  \item ~\\
  \item ~\\\\\\

\end{enumerate}

This process is known as describing the  \underline{\hspace{3cm}} of the categorical variable. We can summarize the distribution of a single categorical variable by using data visualizations: 
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Frequency/Relative Frequency Table
  \item Bar Chart
